<a href="/~theory/"><img src="http://www.ics.uci.edu/~theory/logo/CATOC2.jpg"></a>
<h2><a href="/~theory/269/">CS 269S, Fall 2017: Theory Seminar</a><br>
Bren Hall, Room 1300, 1pm

<hr />
October 27, 2017:</h2>
<h1>
Sorting in the Asymmetric External Memory model
</h1>
<h2>
Nodari Sitchinava
</h2>

<p>
Asymmetric External Memory (AEM) model, introduced by Blelloch et
al. at SPAA 2015, models computations when the data is stored on new
non-volatile memory (NVM) storage, rather than tradition DRAM
memory. The significant difference in NVMs is the fact that the cost
of writing data is significantly higher than the cost of reading
it.  This asymmetry requires new algorithmic techniques, which allow
the trade-off of write accesses for extra read accesses during
computation.
</p>

<p>
In this talk I will present sorting algorithms, which achieve such a
trade-off between read and write accesses in the AEM model. If time
permits, I will also show a lower bound that proves that this
trade-off is asymptotically optimal.
</p>

